Here's a small JavaScript `debounce` function with a brief example of how to use it:

The `debounce` function delays invoking a function until after a specified number of milliseconds have elapsed since the last time it was called:

```javascript
function debounce(func, wait) {
  let timeout;
  return function(...args) {
    clearTimeout(timeout);
    timeout = setTimeout(() => func.apply(this, args), wait);
  };
}

// Example usage:
function logMessage(message) {
  console.log(message);
}

const debouncedLog = debounce(logMessage, 300);

debouncedLog("Hello");
debouncedLog("World");
// Only "World" will be logged after 300ms, as it's the last call within the delay period
```

In this example, the `debouncedLog` function is a debounced version of `logMessage` with a 300ms delay. When `debouncedLog` is called multiple times within the 300ms delay, only the last call will actually invoke `logMessage` after the delay has passed.
